05337nam a22006975i 9780822384007DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20022002ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223840077 a10.1515/97808223840072doi  a(DE-B1597)554174  a(OCoLC)1055302961  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPS374.W39bF74 2002 7aLIT0040202bisacsh04a813/.5093552211 aFreeman, Elizabeth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Wedding Complex :bForms of Belonging in Modern American Culture /cElizabeth Freeman; ed. by Michèle Aina Barale, Eve Kosofsky Sedgwick, Michael Moon, Jonathan Goldberg. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2002] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (310 p.) :b8 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSeries Q : 800tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 Love among the Ruins -- t2 The We of Me: The Member of the Wedding’s Novel Alliances -- t3 ‘‘That Troth Which Failed to Plight’’: Race, the Wedding, and Kin Aesthetics in Absalom, Absalom! -- t4 ‘‘A Diabolical Circle for the Divell to Daunce In’’: Foundational Weddings and the Problem of Civil Marriage -- t5 Honeymoon with a Stranger: Private Couplehood and the Making of the National Subject -- t6 The Immediate Country, or, Heterosexuality in the Age of Mechanical Reproduction -- tCoda -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn The Wedding Complex Elizabeth Freeman explores the significance of the wedding ceremony by asking what the wedding becomes when you separate it from the idea of marriage. Freeman finds that weddings—as performances, fantasies, and rituals of transformation—are sites for imagining and enacting forms of social intimacy other than monogamous heterosexuality. Looking at the history of Anglo-American weddings and their depictions in American literature and popular culture from the antebellum era to the present, she reveals the cluster of queer desires at the heart of the "wedding complex"—longings not for marriage necessarily but for public forms of attachment, ceremony, pageantry, and celebration.Freeman draws on queer theory and social history to focus on a range of texts where weddings do not necessarily lead to legal marriage but instead reflect yearnings for intimate arrangements other than long-term, state-sanctioned, domestic couplehood. Beginning with a look at the debates over gay marriage, she proceeds to consider literary works by Nathaniel Hawthorne, William Faulkner, Carson McCullers, Vladimir Nabokov, and Edgar Allan Poe, along with such Hollywood films as Father of the Bride, The Graduate, and The Godfather. She also discusses less well-known texts such as Su Friedrich’s experimental film First Comes Love and the off-Broadway, interactive dinner play Tony ‘n’ Tina’s Wedding.Offering bold new ways to imagine attachment and belonging, and the public performance and recognition of social intimacy, The Wedding Complex is a major contribution to American studies, queer theory, and cultural studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAmerican fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aCulture in motion pictures. 0aPopular culturezUnited States. 0aSame-sex marriage in literature. 0aSame-sex marriagezUnited States. 0aSexual orientation in literature. 0aWeddings in literature. 0aWeddings in motion pictures. 0aWeddings in popular culture. 0aWeddingszUnited States. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh1 aBarale, Michèle Aina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGoldberg, Jonathan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMoon, Michael, eeditor.4edt4h